'''Cannabis in Estonia''' is illegal, but possession of up to 7.5&nbsp;grams is considered an amount for personal use, and is punished with a fine. Large amounts and distribution are criminal offences and punishable with a custodial sentence of up to 5 years.<ref>{{citation |url = http://www.eupedia.com/europe/maps_of_europe.shtml#cannabis |title = Europe Guide : Maps of Europe by language, religion, population density, hair and eye color, etc |publisher = Eupedia.com |date = 19 April 1994 |accessdate = 2011-02-17 }}</ref> In 2018, the then recently merged [[Municipalities of Estonia|municipality]] of [[:et:Kanepi vald|Kanepi]] in southern Estonia adopted the cannabis leaf as the symbol on its flag and coat of arms.<ref>{{citation |url = https://news.err.ee/687702/kanepi-municipality-residents-choose-cannabis-leaf-for-flag-coat-of-arms |title = Kanepi Municipality residents choose cannabis leaf for flag, coat of arms |publisher = [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |date = 2018-03-06 |accessdate = 2018-08-21 }}</ref> ''[[:et:Kanep|Kanep]]'' is the Estonian word for cannabis. [[Hemp]] was historically used as a product in [[shipbuilding]]. It was traded from the eastern Baltic within the [[Hanseatic League]] and in the sixteenth century directly to the Netherlands for this purpose.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Kasekamp|first1= Andres|date= 2018|title= A History of the Baltic States,|url= |location= London|publisher= [[Palgrave Macmillan]]|page= 34|isbn= 978-1-137-57365-0|author-link= Andres  Kasekamp}}</ref>

