{{Expand French|Malnutrition au Tibet|date=May 2012}}

'''Malnutrition''' is an important health concern in [[Tibet]]. According to a study conducted in 1994/1995 in eleven districts of Tibet, malnutrition affected more than half of the children from 1–7 years old. The major cause was poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/eo20010728a2.html|title=Malnutrition plagues Tibet's children|author=Cesar Chelala|first=|date=July 28, 2001|website=|publisher=Japan Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=May 14, 2012|quote=QUOTE: "In 1996, the Western Consortium for Public Health, a private U.S.-based organization, said 60 percent of the children studied fell drastically below accepted international growth reference values and concluded that the height of Tibetan children was a matter of grave concern. Their data indicated that the children’s shortness was a result of nutritional deficiencies — chronic malnutrition during the first three years of life — rather than the consequence of genetics or altitude, as had been previously suggested."}}</ref>

