{{Underlinked|date=August 2017}}

'''Stealth ownership''' occurs when a larger corporation purchases a smaller enterprise but maintains the packaging and advertising strategies of that smaller company.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Emergent Agriculture: Farming, Sustainability and the Return of the Local Economy|last=Kleppel|first=Gary|last2=Ikerd|first2=John|date=2014-07-22|publisher=New Society Publishers|isbn=9780865717732|language=English}}</ref> It is common for the purchaser not to disclose that it owns the smaller company in hopes of maintaining the acquired company's image.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Emergent Agriculture: Farming, Sustainability and the Return of the Local Economy|last=Kleppel|first=Gary|last2=Ikerd|first2=John|date=2014-07-22|publisher=New Society Publishers|isbn=9780865717732|language=English}}</ref> This phenomenon is very common within the [[organic movement]] and is considered part of the [[Big Organic]] movement that began in the late 1990s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Emergent Agriculture: Farming, Sustainability and the Return of the Local Economy|last=Kleppel|first=Gary|last2=Ikerd|first2=John|date=2014-07-22|publisher=New Society Publishers|isbn=9780865717732|language=English}}</ref>

